  Here's a focused breakdown specifically for Node.js:

  ***

  ## The Core Idea

  gRPC has its **own status code system** — completely separate from HTTP status codes. When a call fails, you get back a `code` (number) and a `details` (string message), not a 404 or 500.

  ***

  ## The Status Codes You'll Actually Use

  | Code | Name                 | When to use                                 |
  | ---- | -------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |
  | 0    | `OK`                 | Success                                     |
  | 1    | `CANCELLED`          | Client cancelled the request                |
  | 2    | `UNKNOWN`            | Something went wrong, no details            |
  | 3    | `INVALID_ARGUMENT`   | Bad input from client (like 422)            |
  | 4    | `DEADLINE_EXCEEDED`  | Took too long                               |
  | 5    | `NOT_FOUND`          | Resource doesn't exist (like 404)           |
  | 6    | `ALREADY_EXISTS`     | Duplicate resource (like 409)               |
  | 7    | `PERMISSION_DENIED`  | Authenticated but not authorized (like 403) |
  | 8    | `RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED` | Rate limited / quota hit                    |
  | 13   | `INTERNAL`           | Server-side bug (like 500)                  |
  | 14   | `UNAVAILABLE`        | Server is down, good for retry logic        |
  | 16   | `UNAUTHENTICATED`    | No valid credentials (like 401)             |

  You won't need all 17 codes early on — the ones above cover ~95% of real scenarios.

  ***

  ## How it looks in Node.js

  **Server side — throwing an error:**

  ```js
  const grpc = require("@grpc/grpc-js");

  function getUser(call, callback) {
    const user = db.find(call.request.id);

    if (!user) {
      return callback({
        code: grpc.status.NOT_FOUND,
        details: `User with id ${call.request.id} not found`,
      });
    }

    callback(null, user);
  }
  ```

  **Client side — catching an error:**

  ```js
  client.getUser({ id: 99 }, (err, response) => {
    if (err) {
      console.log(err.code); // 5
      console.log(err.details); // "User with id 99 not found"
      console.log(err.message); // "5 NOT_FOUND: User with id 99 not found"
      return;
    }
    console.log(response);
  });
  ```

  ***

  ## The Gotcha Most Tutorials Miss

  **Don't use raw numbers** — always use the `grpc.status` enum:

  ```js
  // ❌ bad — magic numbers are fragile
  callback({ code: 5, details: "not found" });

  // ✅ good
  callback({ code: grpc.status.NOT_FOUND, details: "not found" });
  ```

